# Advanced Data Types
- MySQL supports several beyond the basics (INT, VARCHAR, DATE)

1. Advanced Numeric Types
 i. DECIMAL(p,s)/NUMERIC(p,s)
 - extract precision for financial values
 ii. BIGINT 
 - very large integers(IDs,pupulation counts,scientific date)
 iii. BIT(n)
 - binary flags or bit fields(eg. multiple true/false states)
 iv. BOOLEAN/BOOL
 - Alias for TINYTINT(1)
 - used for true/false values.

2. Advanced String & Text Types
  i. TEXT family
  - TINYTEXT,TEXT,MEDIUMTEXT,LONGTEXT
  - stores large text (blogs,articles, documents)
  ii. BLOB family
  - TINYBOLB, BOLB, MEDIUMBOLB, LONGBOLB
  - stores binary data(images files, multimedia).
  iii. ENUM
  - restrict values to a fixed set (e.g. grades A, B, C, D, F)
  iv. SET
  - allows multiple selections from a predefined list (e.g. skills: SQL, Python, ML).

3. JSON Data Types
- stores semi-structured data(nested attributes, arrays).
- Example: {"name":"Aashish","skills":["SQL","Python","ML"]}
- use case: flexible schemas, dynamic attributes, API integration.

4. Spatial(GIS) Data Types
   i. POINT
   - stores a single coordinate(latitude, longitude)
   ii. LINESTRING
   - store paths(roads, routes)
   iii. POLYGON
   - store areas(district boundaries, zones)
   iv. GEOMETRY
   - general type for Spatial objects.
   v. GEOMETRYCOLLECTION
   - stores multiple geometries together.
